<title>Konfigurator: Making Your Own Krusader</title>

<note><para>Konfigurator will be rewritten, some of the information in this handbook can be obsolete.</para></note>

<para>Konfigurator is Krusader's configuration center. Here you can modify the way Krusader does
things and customize it to your own needs. At all times, pressing the <keycap>OK</keycap> button
will apply the changes, pressing <keycap>Cancel</keycap> will cancel them, and pressing
<keycap>Defaults</keycap> will reapply Krusder's "factory" settings. Konfigurator is divided
into pages, each containing items related to that page.</para>

	<sect1 id="konfig-startup">
	<title>The startup page</title>
	<screenshot>
		<screeninfo>Konfigurator startup page</screeninfo>
		<mediaobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kgstartup.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kgstartup.eps" format="EPS"/></imageobject>
		<textobject><phrase>Screenshot</phrase></textobject>
		</mediaobject>
	</screenshot>
	<para>The startup page determines the way that Krusader looks (and works) when it is launched.
	It is divided into two main parts:</para>

	  <variablelist>
	<varlistentry><term><guilabel>Panels</guilabel></term>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Save settings on exit:</keycap> when Krusader launches, the panels current
		directory will be the same as it was, when Krusader was shutdown - providing the location is
		within a local filesystem.</para>
		<para><keycap>Start with the following settings:</keycap> allows you to define a startup status
		for each of the panel in the following manner:
		</para>
	<itemizedlist><listitem><para><keycap>Panel types:</keycap> select one of the available combinations.
				<itemizedlist>
					<listitem><para>List, List</para></listitem>
					<listitem><para>List, Tree</para></listitem>
					<listitem><para>List, Quickview</para></listitem>
					<listitem><para>Tree, List</para></listitem>
					<listitem><para>Quickview, List</para></listitem>
				</itemizedlist>
			</para></listitem>

			<listitem><para><keycap>Panel starts at:</keycap> the following options are available
				<itemizedlist>
					<listitem><para><remark>homepage:</remark> This panel will start at a
					   specified homepage. In this case, you also need to choose a directory in
					   which will be this panel's homepage.</para></listitem>
					<listitem><para><remark>workdir:</remark> This panel will start at the
					   folder it was executed from.</para></listitem>
					<listitem><para><remark>last place it was:</remark> This panel will start
					   at the last directory it was when Krusader was shut down.</para></listitem>
				</itemizedlist>
			</para></listitem>
	</itemizedlist>

	</listitem></varlistentry>

	<varlistentry><term><guilabel>User Interface</guilabel></term>
		<listitem><para>Determine which parts of the user interface are visible during startup.
		<itemizedlist>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Save settings on exit:</keycap> when shutdown, Krusader checks the
			   state of the user interface components, and restores them to the condition they were during
			   shutdown.</para></listitem>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Toolbar visible:</keycap> if checked, the
			   <link linkend="toolbar">toolbar</link> will be visible during startup.</para></listitem>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Statusbar visible:</keycap> if checked, the statusbar will be
			   visible during startup.</para></listitem>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Function keys visible:</keycap> if checked, the
			   <link linkend="fnkeys">function keys bar</link> will be visible during
			   startup.</para></listitem>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Command line visible:</keycap> if checked, the
			   <link linkend="cmdline">command line</link> will be visible during
			   startup.</para></listitem>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Terminal emulator visible:</keycap> if checked, the terminal
			   emulator will be visible during startup.</para></listitem>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Restore last postion and size:</keycap> when launched, Krusader
			    will resize itself to
			    the last size it was when last shutdown. Krusader will also appear in the same location
			    on the screen.</para></listitem>
		</itemizedlist>
		</para></listitem>
	</varlistentry>
	</variablelist>

  </sect1>

	<sect1 id="konfig-lookNfeel">
	<title>The look and feel page</title>
	<screenshot>
		<screeninfo>Konfigurator look and feel page</screeninfo>
		<mediaobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kglookfeel.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kglookfeel.eps" format="EPS"/></imageobject>
		<textobject><phrase>Screenshot</phrase></textobject>
		</mediaobject>
	</screenshot>
	<para>Here you can determine the look and feel of things - which basically means fine-tuning the
	application to you needs. The page is divided into three tabs: <guilabel>General</guilabel>,
	<guilabel>Toolbar</guilabel> and <guilabel>Key-bindings</guilabel>. Since <guilabel>Toolbar</guilabel>
	and <guilabel>Key-bindings</guilabel> are KDE's standard toolbar and keyboard editor, we'll focus on
	the <guilabel>General</guilabel> section:</para>


	<itemizedlist>
	<title id="konfig-lookNfeel-General">General</title>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Warn on exit:</keycap> if checked, Krusader will display an "Are you
		   sure ?" warning when you're trying to shut it down. Otherwise, it will exit without
		   protest.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Minimize to tray:</keycap> if checked, when you minimize Krusader,
		   its icon will appear in the system tray instead of the taskbar.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Show hidden files:</keycap> if checked, Krusader will display the "dot
		   files" which are otherwise hidden.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Automark directories:</keycap> when
		   <link linkend="mark-menu">marking a group of files</link> (either by
		   using Select Group or by using Select All), Krusader will check this option. If it is checked,
		   than directories matching the select criteria will also be marked. Otherwise, only files will be
		   marked.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Case sensitive sorting:</keycap> if checked (the Unix default), than all
		   files beginning with capital letters appear before files beginning with non-capital letters,
		   otherwise, all files begining with a specified letter (capital or otherwise) will appear
		   together.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Panel font:</keycap> allows you to change the font used inside the file
		   lists.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Filelist icon size:</keycap> allows you to change the size of the icons in
		   the file lists. available sizes are 16x16, 22x22, 32x32 and 48x48 pixels.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>HTML viewer's minimal font size:</keycap> when viewing an HTML file
		   (usually using <keycap>F3</keycap>), Krusader invokes KDE's built-in HTML parser. This option
		   sets the minimal font size for the viewer, and aligns other font sizes according to
		   it.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Mouse selection modes:</keycap> three modes are available,
			<itemizedlist>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Classic:</keycap> the way Krusader used to work from day one.
			   Both keys allow selecting files. To select more than one file, hold the
			   <keycap>CTRL</keycap> key and click the <keycap>left</keycap> mouse button. Right-click
			   menu is invoked using a short click on the <keycap>right</keycap> mouse
			   button.</para></listitem>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Left mouse button selects:</keycap> this way, pressing the
			<keycap>left</keycap> mouse button selects files - you can click and select multiple files.
			   Right-click menu is invoked using a short click on the <keycap>right</keycap> mouse
			   button.</para></listitem>
			<listitem><para><keycap>Right button selects:</keycap> this way (sometimes referred to as
			   'total (windows) commander style') the <keycap>left</keycap> mouse button does not select,
			   but sets the current file without affecting the current selection. The
			   <keycap>right</keycap> mouse button selects multiple files and the right-click menu is
			   invoked by <guilabel>pressing and holding</guilabel> the <keycap>right</keycap> mouse
			   button.</para></listitem>
			</itemizedlist>
		</para></listitem>
	</itemizedlist>

	<variablelist>
	<varlistentry><term><guilabel id="konfig-lookNfeel-Toolbar">Toolbar</guilabel></term>
		<listitem><para>Here you can configure the <link linkend="toolbar">Toolbar</link> the way you like.
		  Add the icons of your favorite functions into the Toolbar.</para>
                </listitem>
	</varlistentry>
	</variablelist>

	<variablelist>
	<varlistentry><term><guilabel id="konfig-lookNfeel-KeyBindings">Key-bindings</guilabel></term>
		<listitem><para>Here you can configure the Key-bindings. Configure the Key-bindings
	        of your favorite functions the way you like.</para>
                </listitem>
	</varlistentry>
	</variablelist>


	</sect1>

	<sect1 id="konfig-general">
	<title>The general page</title>
	<screenshot>
		<screeninfo>Konfigurator general page</screeninfo>
		<mediaobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kggeneral.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kggeneral.eps" format="EPS"/></imageobject>
		<textobject><phrase>Screenshot</phrase></textobject>
		</mediaobject>
	</screenshot>
	<para>The following options determine basic aspects of operation:
	<itemizedlist>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Delete files / Move to trash:</keycap> when Krusader deletes files it can
		   either 'really' delete them or move them to the trash folder, thereby making them available via
		   KDE's trash.</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Use mimetype magic:</keycap> mimetype magic is a mechanism which allows
		   Krusader to inspect the files in the panels and determine their type even if the file has no
		   identifying extention. For example, if you take an image file - 'image1.jpg' - and rename it to
		   'image1', Krusader will still know it's an image file and work with it accordingly. However, this
		   mode of operation is slower (while refreshing the panel, or changing directories), so try Krusader
		   with and without mimetype magic and decide what's best for you</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Editor:</keycap> choose what editor will be used when editing a file (via
		   F4).</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Terminal:</keycap> choose what terminal emulator will be used when Krusader
		   opens a console window (via F2, or Commands->Terminal menu option).</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Temp directory:</keycap> this option selects the base directory for
		   Krusader's temporary files. The actual files will be created in separate directories under the 'Temp
		   directory', so that each user running Krusader will have his/her own temporary subdirectories under
		   the chosen directory.

		<note><para>You must choose a temporary directory such that all the users who are running Krusader
		    will have full permissions to it !</para></note></para></listitem>
	</itemizedlist></para>
	</sect1>

	<sect1 id="konfig-advanced">
	<title>The advanced page</title>
	<screenshot>
		<screeninfo>Konfigurator advanced page</screeninfo>
		<mediaobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kgadvanced.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kgadvanced.eps" format="EPS"/></imageobject>
		<textobject><phrase>Screenshot</phrase></textobject>
		</mediaobject>
	</screenshot>
	<para>This page handles more advanced issues, so you should double-check what you do here, since modifying
	things around here <remark>makes Krusader a more powerful AND dangerous tool.</remark></para>
	<para>The page is divided into three parts:</para>
	<variablelist>
	<varlistentry><term><guilabel>General</guilabel></term>
	<listitem>
  <itemizedlist>
		<listitem><para>Note: This function does not exist anymore and is replaced by
		<link linkend="root-mode">Root Mode Krusader (Alt+K)</link></para>
		<para>( I AM ROOT: usually, when doing any operation, Krusader checks permissions. This means that if
		root wants to remove a folder owned by a user, Krusader will not let him/her do that !!! By checking
		this option, you make Krusader assume you are root, which means that Krusader WON'T DO ANY PERMISSION
		CHECKS ! AT ALL ! NOTHING ! This obviously makes life easier for power users, but it also means that if
		you make a mistake, there's no going back ! and you won't even get a warning. USE WITH CAUTION !
		  )</para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Automount filesystems:</keycap> this makes Krusader try to mount a
		 filesystem before entering it. For example, if you'd click on /mnt/cdrom (and /mnt/cdrom appears in
		 /etc/fstab as a mount point), Krusader will check if it is mounted. If not, it will try and mount it
		 for you and then enter, so that you'd see the contents of your cdrom. Note, however, that Krusader
		 will NOT unmount when exiting /mnt/cdrom.</para></listitem>
	</itemizedlist></listitem>
	</varlistentry>
	<varlistentry>
	<term><guilabel>Confirmations</guilabel></term>
		<listitem><para>By checking the options in this section, you'll make Krusader ask for confirmation
		   before doing the specific action. Otherwise, the actions will be done without warning.</para>
	</listitem></varlistentry>
	<varlistentry>
	<term><guilabel>Fine-Tuning</guilabel></term>
	<listitem><itemizedlist>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Icon cache size:</keycap> Krusader uses an icon cache, so it won't have to
		  reload icons that were already used before. Ofcourse, as the cache grows bigger, it can store more
		  icons and further speed operations, but the memory footprint of Krusader will be
		  bigger.</para></listitem>
	</itemizedlist>
	</listitem></varlistentry>
	</variablelist>
	</sect1>

	<sect1 id="konfig-archives">
	<title>The archives page</title>
	<screenshot>
		<screeninfo>Konfigurator archives page</screeninfo>
		<mediaobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kgarchives.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
		<imageobject><imagedata fileref="kgarchives.eps" format="EPS"/></imageobject>
		<textobject><phrase>Screenshot</phrase></textobject>
		</mediaobject>
	</screenshot>
	<para>This page handles the way Krusader works with archives. In the <guilabel>General</guilabel> section
	you'll see a list of archive formats. Some are checked and some are grayed-out. The ones that are available
	(not grayed-out) are supported by Krusader. If  you check them, than Krusader will handle them transparently
	and let you open them as folders. Otherwise, Krusader will attempt to invoke an application which opens that
	type of archive. If a certain archive is grayed-out, it means that Krusader couldn't find the appropriate
	executables in the PATH (to handle ZIP archives, Krusader needs 'unzip' and 'zip' executables).</para>
	<para>If you've installed a certain archive application (let's say 'arj') and want Krusader to know about
	it, just click the 'Auto Configure' button. Krusader will search for all supported executables, and print
	a report regarding what archives can be handled. If all went well, the new archive will be availble and
	checked.
  <note><para>Please install new archives to your PATH (ie: /usr/bin; /usr/local/bin etc.)</para></note></para>
	<para><guilabel>Fine-Tuning</guilabel>
	<itemizedlist>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Allow moving into archives:</keycap> this option allows you to move files
		  into an archive (as opposed to just copying into the archive). The down side is that if a power
		  failure occurs during the process, the files that were moved might already be deleted, but not yet
		  packed into the archive.
    <note><para> If such thing happens, the file are NOT LOST. they were actually moved into a subfolder in the
		Krusader's temp directory. You can search that directory and find your files, safe and sound.
		</para></note></para></listitem>
		<listitem><para><keycap>Test archives when finished packing:</keycap> this option automatically
		   runs a test on a newly packed archive. It is safer, but takes longer.</para></listitem>
	</itemizedlist></para>

 </sect1>

